    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 10 with a clear offensive ceiling anchored by **Yordan Alvarez** (84.61) and **Junior Caminero** (78.33). **Yordan Alvarez** is our premier play, benefiting from a soft matchup against Emerson Hancock; his high xwOBA suggests he will exploit the SP Skill rating, even with the park factor dragging slightly. **Junior Caminero** also projects as an elite start, taking advantage of a favorable matchup against Luis Gil, whose 5.74 xERA is the most exploitable mark on our slate. **Christian Yelich** rounds out our top-tier trio at 74.33, as the platoon advantage against Jake Irvin elevates him well above his baseline projection.\n\nWe are hunting stolen bases today, which makes the inclusion of **Hyeseong Kim** (61.92) a strategic necessity. Despite being tucked into the 8-hole, **Hyeseong Kim** faces a pitcher with a slow delivery, and the projected wind blowing out at the venue provides a boost that keeps him comfortably above our efficiency floor. Conversely, the toughest call today was omitting **Josh Smith** (53.82). While he carries a strong platoon edge and would typically be a beneficiary of stolen base opportunities against a slow pitcher, he falls just outside the starting nine due to his low batting order placement and a daunting matchup against the elite stuff of Tyler Glasnow, which effectively capped his daily ceiling.\n\nLineup stability remains a primary risk as we await official word on several key contributors. **Chase Meidroth** is currently holding a 55.14 score, but he carries a 31% rain risk that could lead to a mid-game exit or a PPD situation. We are also monitoring the confirmed orders for **Caleb Durbin**, **Christian Yelich**, **Yordan Alvarez**, and **Hyeseong Kim**. Should any of these players move down significantly in their respective orders, we may see their efficiency scores dip near our 40.0 threshold, necessitating a pivot to our bench depth to maximize our 5x5 Roto output.",
